<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Flying Horse on the Move</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Susan Loden
		
		<span class="date">September 18, 2003</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
			
				<ul>
				<li> www.flying-horse-editions.org.</li>
			
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=002400411a631c20faa3ccc32a0414b"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			Flying Horse Edition fine arts publishing house at the University of Central Florida is celebrating its regeneration in a new 5,000-square-foot facility in the Orlando Tech Center in the Central Florida Research Park.

A $250,000 grant from an Orlando foundation and partnerships with four publishing businesses brought expansion and the introduction of computer technology. Flying Horse has more than doubled in size and its output of museum-quality, limited-edition art books and prints by internationally renowned artists and authors.

The 13-year-old Flying Horse will celebrate expansion by inviting artists, collectors and investors to a series of soirees in its new studio and gallery. The opening at 7 p.m. Sept. 27 will debut of a multi-colored etching, "Past Forgetting," created by San Francisco artist Timothy Berry during a visit to Flying Horse. Berry founded Teaberry Press, featured this year in the UCF Art Gallerys exhibition, "Teaberry Press: The Intimate Collection."

The partners, H2O Graphics, Robert Beck, Hoopsnake Press and Gardyloo Handmade Books, provide master-level expertise, equipment and materials for all nonprofit FHE projects and graphic arts research. Independently, they offer the fine arts community a full array of ancient and modern publishing and printing techniques, including non-toxic water-based screenprinting, lithography, woodcuts and etching.

"Our focus is on publishing works by leading contemporary artists and authors," says Flying Horse Director Ryan Burkhart, the artist/owner of H2O Graphics. "We bring them together with our faculty, Flying Horse partners and students to create significant works of art at the university, while experimenting with ancient and modern methods. Our students and faculty are enriched by this research and its a nice opportunity to add substantive pieces of artwork to our Art Department collection and to the Special Collections Department of the UCF Library." 

Berry has shown in more than 20 solo exhibitions and many group exhibits in the past 17 years. His work is in many public and private collections including the Achenbach Collection, Bank of America Collection and the Belfast Museum of Art. In England, his prints can be seen in the Oldham Museum, the Royal Albert Museum and the Victoria and Albert Museum.

"The Orlando Museum of Art, Cornell Fine Arts Museum and the UCF Art Gallery do a great job exhibiting a lot of significant contemporary work, keeping fine art viable in the area. Were adding to that by bringing premier award-winning artists to Orlando to make fine art books and prints in our studio. This gives collectors and investors the opportunity to be exposed to visiting artists, while adding significant works to their collections."

Private collectors and institutions provide all funds for FHE projects. Each year donors are rewarded with gifts of Flying Horse prints and books, according to each patrons participation level. 

"Were really working to create limited edition books in a very unique way," Burkhart says. "Its a labor of love printed on a letterpress that was state-of-the-art in the 1950s. Its a somewhat antiquated way to make a book -- a distinctive, handmade book."

This fall, Flying Horse will release its limited edition book, "Lonely Tylenol," by Guggenheim Museum of Art prize-winning artist David Humphrey, who is a two-time National Endowment for the Arts recipient, and Sharon Mesmer, who has a New York Foundation for the Arts grant in poetry. Canadian artist Medrie MacPhee and American writer Ted Mooney will craft the next Flying Horse book in the spring.

		
	
